<p>Using our set notation:</p>

<p>\(A \bigtriangleup B = \{x \vert (x \in A\) and \(x \notin B)\) or \((x \notin A\) and \(x \in B)\}\)</p>

<p>Equivalently:</p>

\[A \bigtriangleup B = (A-B) \cup (B-A)\]

<p>\(A \bigtriangleup B = (A \cup B) - (A \cap B)\), where \(\bigtriangleup\)</p>

<p>A different way to view symmetric difference \(\bigtriangleup\) is in terms of the <em>exclusive OR</em> operation, which is denoted as \(XOR\) or \(\oplus\).</p>

\[A \bigtriangleup B = \{ x \vert (x \in A) \oplus (x \in B) \}\]

<p>\(XOR,\) \(\oplus,\) is a logical binary operation which output values {True, False}. It is the case that \(x \oplus y\) is true only when the input terms \(x\) and \(y\) differ as shown in the truth table below:</p>

